Medical Disclaimer for Tuna
Last Updated: January 13, 2026

Tuna ("we," "our," or "us") provides a mobile application designed to assist users in scanning food labels. This Medical Disclaimer explains the limitations of our technology and the responsibilities of the user.

Not Medical Advice
Informational Purposes Only: The content provided by Tuna, including allergen alerts, ingredient analysis, and health scores, is for informational purposes only.

No Professional Relationship: Use of this app does not create a doctor-patient or any other professional healthcare relationship.

Consult Professionals: Always seek the advice of a physician, allergist, or other qualified health provider with any questions regarding a medical condition or dietary restrictions.

Accuracy of AI and Technology
AI Limitations: Tuna utilizes advanced AI (Google Gemini) and OCR technology to read and interpret labels. While we strive for accuracy, AI can make mistakes, misread text, or fail to identify hidden allergens.

No Guarantee: We do not guarantee that the information provided is 100% accurate, complete, or up-to-date. Physical labels and manufacturer formulations may change without notice.

User Responsibility
Mandatory Physical Verification: You must always verify the ingredients on the physical product label before consuming any food item.

High-Risk Allergies: If you have life-threatening allergies (such as anaphylactic reactions), do not rely solely on this app for your safety.

Data Input: The accuracy of Tuna’s analysis depends on the quality of the image captured and the profile information you provide.

Limitation of Liability
Use at Your Own Risk: You agree that your use of the app is at your sole risk.

No Liability: Ahmet Tayyip Zorlutuna and the Tuna development team shall not be held liable for any adverse reactions, allergic incidents, or health issues arising from the use of the app or reliance on its data.

Emergency Situations
Not for Emergencies: Tuna is not a tool for emergency response. In the event of an allergic reaction or medical emergency, contact your local emergency services (e.g., 112 or 911) immediately.

